Welcome to Apollo

As you scroll down, we will help you learn the ins and outs of Apollo.

What is Apollo?

Apollo is a fact checking tool that helps you stay vigilant on Twitter by showing you relevant insights on news articles other users post or share.

Is Apollo going to tell me what's right and wrong?

Apollo doesn’t tell you what to believe. Instead, Apollo gives you the information to make your own decision.

Let's show you how it works

When will Apollo show up?

When enabled, you will find a “Learn more about this article” button attached to every article link on your twitter feed.

How do I use Apollo?

When you click the “Learn more about this article” button, Apollo will open a side panel where you’ll find relevant additional information that helps keep you informed

Understand who wrote it

If an article has an attached author, Apollo will find them. If an article has no author listed, this may be a sign of a less credible source.

In both cases, we encourage you to evaluate the quality of the source that published the information.

See what emotions articles want you to feel

Did you know that misinformation is significantly more likely to make readers feel negative emotions compared to accurate information? [read study]  

Apollo informs you when an article is doing this.

Related Articles

To help you learn more about the topic from different publishers and perspectives, Apollo will find related articles that relate to the core topic.

Ready to get started?
